  "prompt": "What happens to your phlegm after swallowing it?",
  "response": "When you swallow phlegm, it follows the same path as food and other substances you ingest. Here\u2019s what happens:\n\n1. **Travels to the Stomach**: The phlegm moves down your esophagus and into your stomach, aided by the muscular contractions of peristalsis.\n\n2. **Stomach Acid Breaks It Down**: Once in the stomach, the phlegm is exposed to gastric acid, which contains hydrochloric acid and digestive enzymes. These substances break down the components of the phlegm, such as mucus, proteins, and any trapped bacteria or viruses.\n\n3. **Absorption and Elimination**: The broken-down components are then processed further in the small intestine, where nutrients (if any) are absorbed. The remaining waste moves into the large intestine and is eventually excreted as feces.\n\n4. **Immune System Involvement**: If the phlegm contains pathogens (like bacteria or viruses), your stomach acid helps neutralize them. Additionally, your immune system may identify and attack any harmful substances that survive the stomach's acidic environment.\n\nSwallowing phlegm is generally harmless for most people, as the digestive system is equipped to handle it. However, if the phlegm is caused by an infection or contains harmful pathogens, it\u2019s still important to address the underlying condition (e.g., by staying hydrated, resting, or seeking medical attention if necessary).",
